one of the inspirations for jun's personality was the idea that honey badgers are not afraid of death, but instead of something aggressive I repurposed it into whatever this is (also took the idea of their loose, baggy skin as you can see)
also it introduces part of alcyone's moral impetus (something jun seemed reluctant to give. what is the actual reason he seemed hesitant I wonder)

again juns a lot less intense than he could be here but this was meant to highlight other points of his personality. and also question the motivations and meanings of the things he says vs the way alcyone is interpreting them (who is too overwhelmed to notice some worrying shit)

loved messing with framing and action and movement which is what I really wanted most out of this. it was supposed to be fucking. monochromatic to be easier. but I kept getting ideas in my head. I could have pushed myself even worse believe me

anyway god its nice to play around with low-stakes pokemon ocs to make something like that. I'm not the happiest with the writing (but still much less stilted than what I usually put out, which is impressive for something written on a whim) and alcyone is a bit plain atm but

I said before I think attempts to make him deeper ironically make him flatter as a character.  to elaborate on that I think its not that he isn't ""deep"" but people need to acknowledge what actually made him this way for what it is. he is so much more impactful that way

and he never will. fear will make him worse and stability will make him worse and there is no angle to convince him otherwise and the snowball will only roll faster. its not sustainable and his fate is sealed and it will destroy him and he is deeply human in the worst way for it

and it is bc of this that he'll never "come to his senses" and realize the error of his ways. he'll never reflect on it. instead of an inherently good person who had to turn to terrible acts, he is someone who never had to and was never driven to learn compassion

he is sick. he is very sick. the human brain should not ever get to this point it has with him. but what brought him here is not trauma, but entirely banal, acceptable things he was rewarded for. the wedge was driven through and he was stunted by a working system

its no big orchestrated grand plan. its pure, gruesome impulse and reflex. he's one of the only characters to make my skin crawl bc the things that have led to him acting this way in his worst moments have nothing to do with being victimized or hurt. nothing sympathetic

I can say a lot about his superiority complex, his completely fucked and detached relationship to the rest of humanity, the snowballing of his status and career to someone who manipulates and kills. what brings it all together for me are those horrific violent terrible meltdowns

even so, I still NEED something that very much grounds and humanizes them for me to grip onto. and I think thats why eiji, of all the fucked up little evil characters out there, is the one thats compelling to me when anyone adjacent to him and more sympathetic to him does not.

worth mentioning that BIAS's voice sounds like a generic female voice-over you get from like siri or alexa or w/e, except for the added glitchy starting/stopping/repetition/etc.

that is not to say BIAS doesn't actually have a character or personality, but its intentionally ambiguous. I couple of the words I use to describe it are "extrospective", "people-pleasing", and "protective": specific words to make things fuzzier
(I do think BIAS might genuinely be the most powerful of the team as it keeps oneshotting everything it shouldn't. that modest sure is nature)

it is the one thing that actually unsettles jun, while yua tends to project and anthropomorphize it for companionship. masuyo and harlow generally don't give too much of a shit beyond how it helps in battle, and being kind of afraid of its power

BIAS as a character among the whole dynamic is pretty interesting, since the most important thing about it is the way other characters react to an interpret the weird fucked up virtual being from the future that they cannot possibly wrap their head around

despite my own bias against this writing structure, I don't think its an objectionably bad format. the plot is a backseat and more just a prompt to show and talk about these characters more real-world problems.

its interesting because I feel like because of these things he would be fun to work with artistically and theorize about, but I have a problem where even if my theories about him hold some water, they aren't "real" enough for my brain. the struggle.

it gives him some degree of open-endedness to his motivations in what he does, and it makes him fascinating to me conceptually as a character. as something for me to latch onto though, I think he falls JUST short of giving me enough of a solid structure for my brain to hold onto

tangentially I think this is why I haven't quite managed to attach to shiba in the way everyone around me has. he is very interesting in the sense that you also get lots of details about him strewn about the game, but mostly by other characters interpreting him, than him directly

but the situation is more awkward for most other ppl, especially if they don't have a prior reason to feel invested enough to put in the effort. characters that aren't spelled out for you but aren't exactly open-ended either exist in this very weird place for sure

I think that is precisely why these characters are like catnip to me, while are also intimidating and hard to approach for others. barely anything is directly spelled out and my analytic brain gets to go rabid pouring over little things that are small, but solid and "real" to me

you can build upon it, but like its not very malleable? and its such an all-encompassing structure formed of little behaviors and motivations so that you can't really branch off from what is there either

kanon and motoi rly are characters with tons of small, missable nuances in the way they act and if you manage to see them all and play connect the dots, you'll find yourself with a fairly solid, rigid structure, that doesn't leave /that/ much wiggle room for free interpretation

anyway thats my essay on why in a post-canon revival situation she should become just some feral fucking animal and also never see the wicked twisters ever again. its about the catharsis xoxoxo

motoi has nothing under his mask, but he never managed to form anything there to begin with. but kanon, if she continued this trajectory of repression, would self-cannibalize and obliterate herself into nothing

at what point does acting the way she always has been to lead her team start feeling so much less natural, and more like straining to put on a fabricated performance? at what point will she start emphasizing more and more with motoi?
it will fester and eat away at her from within, and that connection between who she is and who she projects herself to be will slowly degrade more and more. she may not even notice it as it happens

so what happens when she continues to feel so much and she continues to try repressing it all, while meticulously maintaining the walls she has built so that they will never be destroyed? well. then the only thing left to be destroyed is her sense of self

anyway I went on a tangent there but the point I was trying to make is definitely this rift exists between kanon and the rest of the variabeauties, likely due to what she thinks she must be to be their leader. and so she keeps those walls up to maintain the image they believe in

and then you have w2d5, and the extent of the strain the team members are under and what insane things they are doing behind their leaders backs to cope. its different from the drs in w1d5, where they were communicable with those around them about their wants and desires
I also very much notice how w2d2 highlighted how the variabeauties and purehearts were willing to leak information against their leader's wishes

many times, especially on scramble slam days, it becomes very apparent how much she will act seperately from the rest of her team and leave them to their own devices, if she even chooses to act with them to begin with. the priority difference is very stark
the variabeauties though... they love her. they adore her. they idolize her. but it is pretty apparent how shallow that is, as well as her own maintenance of that image to keep her team hopeful.

I don't think its too much of a stretch to say, in a post-revival scenario, he would end up the most well-adjusted. in spite of all the intense pain and suffering he has endured, he has never alienated himself

but bc of this hes never at odds with who he is, and neither are his teammates. they see all of this of him and continue to fully respect and support him, and of all the teams theyre the ones most engaged w/ his plans and strategies. there is little distance btwn him and his team

compare to fuya, who also cannot stop feeling everything happening to him all the time like she does, but unlike her he has no ability to hide or obscure his suffering. they are on display at all times whether he likes it or not

but with that constant level of control with everyone comes constant distance from everyone. there is no possible way she would have someone she could be open to, if she could even be capable of that. especially if you think all the players only met after joining the reapers game

the words she chooses, her delivery, the double meanings she injects, how she might be the one non-main character with the most expressions and body language in the game but theyre clearly controlled and used with purpose. the level of control over ambiguity she has is terrifying

its true that on the surface, she is a genuine person. everything she picks and chooses to reveal is genuine, which is objectively something that everyone does between interacting with different people. but with her and the situation she is in, its so incredibly extreme
unlike motoi, whose self-destruction came about via a clear and distinct fabrication of the self, kanon's is much muddier and comes about through intense obscuration and repression
